  "prompt": "Why are fruits so expensive in Japan?",
  "response": "Fruits in Japan are expensive due to several factors:\n\n1. Cultivation methods\n- Extremely careful and precise farming techniques\n- Labor-intensive cultivation processes\n- Limited agricultural land\n- Strict quality control standards\n\n2. Cultural significance\n- Fruits are often seen as luxury gifts\n- Considered premium products\n- Used for special occasions and presentations\n\n3. Geographic constraints\n- Limited farmland\n- Mountainous terrain reducing agricultural space\n- High land costs\n\n4. Selective breeding\n- Farmers develop unique, perfect-looking fruits\n- Focus on appearance, size, and taste\n- Specialized varieties like square watermelons\n\n5. High production costs\n- Expensive agricultural inputs\n- Advanced technology in farming\n- High labor wages\n\n6. Limited imports\n- Strict import regulations\n- High tariffs on foreign fruits\n- Preference for domestically grown produce\n\n7. Gifting culture\n- Premium, perfectly shaped fruits are expensive status symbols\n- Often given as high-end gifts\n- Some fruits can cost hundreds of dollars\n\n8. Climate challenges\n- Need for greenhouse cultivation\n- Complex irrigation and protection systems\n- Additional expenses for maintaining optimal growing conditions\n\nThese factors combine to make Japanese fruits significantly more expensive compared to other countries.",
